summary:
Here’s some tips on making yourself feel a little bit more healthy.
1: Make sure to brush your teeth at least once a day. That...
body:
Here’s some tips on making yourself feel a little bit more healthy.

1: Make sure to brush your teeth at least once a day. That minty freshness will make you feel nice.

-

2: Use deodorant or deodorant spray. I‘m a woman and I actually use Old Spice and it lasts for most of the day. ((Also ever since I started using old spice a bunch of cute girls at my college been saying I smell nice👌))

-

3: Drink some water. I’m a hardcore water drinker, about 6-8 cups a day. You don’t need to do that, even drinking water once or twice more than usual will make you feel some health improvements.

-

4: If you can, eat more meat and vegetables and less bread, pasta and potatoes with your meals. This helped me gain muscle and lose fat. I still enjoy breadsticks and fried potatoes once and a while, but I eat it s lot less now.

-

5: Healthy food is expensive, don’t feel bad for not affording it. Trust me, unhealthy food is better than no food. Just try your best to have three meals a day.

-

6: Skipping meals is really unhealthy. I used to skip meals and think it helped me lose weight but it didn’t. What happened was that I’d skip breakfast and lunch and end up eating a shit ton of food during dinner, causing me to gain more weight. Make sure to eat three full meals a day plus snacks! This will help you from overeating, I promise.

-

7: Enjoy things. Reward yourself for doing a good job. Being too strict on your diet is going to make it too difficult and you are more likely to give up. Once or twice a week, award yourself with candy or icecream! You deserve it.

-

8: Do some stretching to help with stiff muscles. There are plenty of videos and websites you can use to see some good stretching instructions.

-

9: Sleep makes you healthy. Try to at least get some sleep.

-

10: Watch movies that you like. You can do this alone even. If you’re sad or lonely I suggest cartoons, or comedy! Or something fun and action packed like some of the Marvel movies.

-

11: Do things that you like. Doing things that you like relaxes you, it helps take stress away. Like I draw and paint, it makes my day a little better.

-

12: Try to be more social! Text your friends, talk to someone. Do something, this will help you from being lonely. Trust me, texting your friends even will brighten up your day a little . If your friends are busy feel free to text me lmao

-

13: Sometimes you will have bad days, trust me. I have them too. Just remember that bad days come and go, things get better. If you really need help, please talk to a close friend or family member, don’t struggle alone.

summary: This hygiene question has the internet divided
title: This hygiene question has the internet divided
body:
We all know that Twitter is the place to go for a debate.

This one conundrum, though, has got thousands of people scratching their heads.

Twitter user, Connor Arpwel, created a poll asking a fairly simple (on the surface) question.

Do you wash your legs when you take a shower?

Do you wash your legs when you take a shower?

— Conor Arpwel 🌹🧰🌾 (@Arpwel) May 9, 2019

The question quickly went viral, amassing over half a million votes in one day.

It seems like there’s a fairly obvious answer - how does one go about not washing their legs in the shower?

But, 20 per cent of people have confessed that, in fact, they skip their legs altogether during shower time.

The surprising stat has led to thousands of bewildered comments circulating online.

READ MORE: Are cold showers really that good for you?

One user wrote: “I just found out my husband doesn’t wash his legs in the shower we gotta divorce now…”

Another agreed: “Once you’re IN the shower… why would u skip your legs??? If you wash your car, and skip the doors… did you really wash it?!”

I missed the debate yesterday but I feel like you don’t really need to wash your legs, you wash your top ¾ and the soap and water runs down. Unless you’re just extraordinarily dirty for some reason,

— PAPI BLANCO 🌹 (@PizzaAndWhiskey) May 10, 2019

Conor Arpwel created such a stir he decided to release a light-hearted “official statement” on the matter.

“My name is Conor Arpwel and I am a leg washer.” He began.

“Leg washing is an important component of my cleanliness regimen, but also I’m not out to get people who don’t wash their legs for various reasons.”

READ MORE: British people vote for showers over baths

Not everybody believed there was a need to wash your legs in the shower, though. After all, the soap runs down your body.

One user said: “I feel like you don’t really need to wash your legs, you wash your top ¾ and the soap and water runs down. Unless you’re just extraordinarily dirty for some reason.”

The debate didn’t end there, though, after one user made another - equally important - observation.

He said: “After we get over the hurdle of washing our legs, i would like to call to everyone’s attention the need to also wash one’s feet.”

We look forward to the Twitter poll 2.0.

He said: “After we get over the hurdle of washing our legs, i would like to call to everyone’s attention the need to also wash one’s feet.”

We look forward to the Twitter poll 2.0.

trail.content_raw:
We all know that Twitter is the place to go for a debate.

This one conundrum, though, has got thousands of people scratching their heads.

Twitter user, Connor Arpwel, created a poll asking a fairly simple (on the surface) question.

Do you wash your legs when you take a shower?

Do you wash your legs when you take a shower?

— Conor Arpwel 🌹🧰🌾 (@Arpwel) May 9, 2019

The question quickly went viral, amassing over half a million votes in one day.

It seems like there’s a fairly obvious answer - how does one go about not washing their legs in the shower?

But, 20 per cent of people have confessed that, in fact, they skip their legs altogether during shower time.

The surprising stat has led to thousands of bewildered comments circulating online.

READ MORE: Are cold showers really that good for you?

One user wrote: “I just found out my husband doesn’t wash his legs in the shower we gotta divorce now…”

Another agreed: “Once you’re IN the shower… why would u skip your legs??? If you wash your car, and skip the doors… did you really wash it?!”

I missed the debate yesterday but I feel like you don’t really need to wash your legs, you wash your top ¾ and the soap and water runs down. Unless you’re just extraordinarily dirty for some reason,

— PAPI BLANCO 🌹 (@PizzaAndWhiskey) May 10, 2019

Conor Arpwel created such a stir he decided to release a light-hearted “official statement” on the matter.

“My name is Conor Arpwel and I am a leg washer.” He began.

“Leg washing is an important component of my cleanliness regimen, but also I’m not out to get people who don’t wash their legs for various reasons.”

He said: “After we get over the hurdle of washing our legs, i would like to call to everyone’s attention the need to also wash one’s feet.”

We look forward to the Twitter poll 2.0.

summary: HCSM News ~ 2 young Canadian brothers — a life-threatening disease— and the harsh reality of drug prices
title: HCSM News ~ 2 young Canadian brothers — a life-threatening disease— and the harsh reality of drug prices
body:
This week’s story of two young Canadian brothers with cystic fibrosis reveals a bleak reality — only one has access to a promising new medication in a clinical trial, while a similar drug that could help his brother is too expensive. But access to the manufacturer’s drugs is not just a problem in Canada. There are bitter fights in other jurisdictions over how much the company is charging.



Read more from CBC https://www.cbc.ca/news/health/cystic-fibrosis-vertex-cadth-orphan-drugs-prices-health-technology-assessment-1.5132294?cmp=rss
